# Tailwind Usage Rules

This file defines how Tailwind is used as a runtime utility layer in a CSS-first (Tailwind v4) architecture.

Tailwind is NOT a design system. It is a styling application layer over design tokens.

---

# 1. Role of Tailwind

Tailwind is:

- a utility layer for applying styles
- a consumer of CSS design tokens (`@theme`)
- an implementation detail of the UI system

Tailwind is NOT:

- a design system
- a source of truth for colors, spacing, or typography
- a place to define visual rules per feature

Rule:
- Tailwind applies design, it does not define design

---

# 2. Token-First Enforcement (Critical)

All styling must originate from the design-token system.

Allowed:
- semantic classes (bg-background, text-foreground, border-border)
- spacing scale derived from tokens
- radius scale derived from tokens
- typography scale derived from tokens

Forbidden:
- hex colors
- arbitrary color values
- feature-specific styling systems
- bypassing semantic tokens via raw values

Rule:
- Tailwind utilities must map to design tokens only

---

# 3. CSS-First Model (Tailwind v4)

This system assumes Tailwind v4 architecture:

- tokens are defined in CSS via `@theme`
- Tailwind consumes these tokens at runtime
- no reliance on tailwind.config as design source

Rule:
- CSS tokens are the source of truth, not Tailwind configuration

---

# 4. ClassName Composition Rules

- use cn() for conditional class composition
- avoid manual string concatenation
- keep className declarative, not logic-heavy
- avoid overly long utility chains without structure

Rule:
- className must remain readable and compositional

---

# 5. Arbitrary Values Policy

Arbitrary values are strongly restricted.

Allowed only when:
- no semantic token exists
- and the value is explicitly justified as an exception

Forbidden:
- routine use of px-[...]
- custom colors in brackets
- ad-hoc spacing systems per feature

Rule:
- arbitrary values are exceptions, not a pattern

---

# 6. Styling Consistency Rule

- spacing must follow system scale
- colors must follow semantic tokens
- typography must follow global scale
- radius must follow defined system

Rule:
- visual consistency overrides local preference

---

# 7. Feature-Level Styling Restriction

Features are NOT allowed to define styling systems.

Forbidden in features:
- custom color systems
- custom spacing systems
- visual overrides that break token consistency

Allowed:
- composition of shared/ui and primitives
- minimal layout adjustments within system constraints

Rule:
- features consume styling system, they do not define it

---

# 8. shadcn/ui Compatibility Rule

- shadcn components must be styled only via Tailwind tokens
- no direct visual overrides outside system constraints
- all styling must remain consistent with design-tokens.mdc

Rule:
- Tailwind + shadcn must operate on the same token system

---

# 9. Anti-Patterns

Forbidden:

- arbitrary styling per feature
- bypassing design tokens
- inconsistent spacing or color usage
- treating Tailwind as a design system
- uncontrolled utility proliferation
- per-component visual systems

---

# 10. System Philosophy

Tailwind is a controlled execution layer over a token-based design system.

This ensures:

- consistent UI across all features
- no visual fragmentation
- predictable styling behavior
- long-term maintainability of UI design language